{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Emerald, Accountability, and AI Policy in Academic Publishing\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community centers around Emerald, an academic publisher committed to ethical and transparent use of AI tools. Key entities include ACCOUNTABILITY, POLICY, and various stakeholders such as authors, editors, and peer reviewers. These entities are interconnected through relationships that emphasize transparency, disclosure, human oversight, and compliance with AI governance standards. The community reflects a growing consensus among publishers and academic institutions on responsible AI integration.\",\n    \"rating\": 9.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The text is highly significant for understanding the evolving landscape of AI in academic publishing, covering essential aspects like accountability, transparency, and policy compliance.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Emerald's role as a leader in AI policy development\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Emerald is a central entity in this community, having developed comprehensive policies to govern the use of AI tools in academic publishing. Its policies emphasize ethical standards, transparency, and human oversight, reflecting its commitment to maintaining research integrity. For example, Emerald requires authors to disclose the use of AI technology in their submissions, ensuring transparency and trust in scholarly communication [records: Entities (81), Relationships (368, 321, 240, 318)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Accountability as a core principle in AI governance\",\n            \"explanation\": \"ACCOUNTABILITY is a foundational concept in this community, representing the shared responsibility of authors, editors, and publishers to uphold ethical standards in the use of AI tools. This includes ensuring that AI-generated content is accurate, original, and properly attributed. Authors, for instance, are held accountable for the integrity of their work, including any AI-assisted content they submit [records: Entities (27), Relationships (129, 373, 375, 195)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POLICY as a unifying framework for AI governance\",\n            \"explanation\": \"POLICY serves as a unifying framework across multiple stakeholders, including major publishers like BMJ, Elsevier, Wiley, and Springer Nature, as well as organizations like ICMJE and IEEE. These policies address critical areas such as transparency, authorship, disclosure, and copyright, aiming to ensure responsible AI integration while maintaining scholarly standards. For example, policies require authors to disclose the use of AI tools in both cover letters and manuscripts, reinforcing transparency in the publication process [records: Entities (61), Relationships (258, 321, 243, 295)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Human oversight as a safeguard against AI bias and errors\",\n            \"explanation\": \"HUMAN OVERSIGHT is a key component of AI governance in this community, emphasizing the need for human control over AI-generated outcomes to prevent bias and ensure quality. Emerald, for instance, mandates human oversight of AI tools to prevent algorithmic bias and ensure the accuracy of research outputs. This practice aligns with broader efforts to maintain fairness and reliability in academic publishing [records: Entities (104), Relationships (399, 263, 245, 439)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"ICMJE's guidelines on AI-assisted technologies\",\n            \"explanation\": \"ICMJE plays a significant role in shaping AI governance by providing guidelines for authors on the use of AI-assisted technologies. These guidelines require authors to describe how AI tools were used in their work and to disclose their usage at submission. This ensures that AI-assisted research is transparent and ethically sound, supporting the broader goal of maintaining trust in academic publishing [records: Entities (106), Relationships (377, 323, 296)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Transparency requirements in AI use\",\n            \"explanation\": \"TRANSPARENCY is a central element of AI governance in this community, with policies mandating detailed disclosure of AI tool usage throughout the publication process. Emerald, for example, requires authors to disclose the use of AI technology in their submissions, ensuring that readers can assess the reliability and originality of the work. This emphasis on transparency helps maintain the integrity of scholarly communication in the age of AI [records: Entities (24), Relationships (243, 246, 240, 321)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Authorship and AI: Ensuring human agency remains central\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The AUTHORSHIP framework reinforces the principle that AI tools cannot be listed as authors, and authors are fully responsible for the content of their work. This policy ensures that human agency remains central to the research and publication process, even as AI tools are increasingly used to support writing and analysis. For instance, ICMJE explicitly states that AI tools cannot be considered authors, and authors must take full responsibility for their work [records: Entities (295), Relationships (295, 296, 377)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Compliance with legal and ethical standards in AI use\",\n            \"explanation\": \"COMPLIANCE is a critical aspect of AI governance, ensuring that AI tools are used in accordance with legal, ethical, and transparent standards. Policies require adherence to these standards, which include protecting the rights of authors and publishers from unauthorized AI use, ensuring data privacy, and addressing potential biases in AI systems. Emerald, for example, enforces confidentiality in the peer review process and prohibits the use of AI tools to evaluate submitted materials [records: Entities (35), Relationships (337, 456, 344, 438)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"AI detection software as a tool for enforcing policies\",\n            \"explanation\": \"AI detection software is used to enforce AI policies by identifying machine-generated content, helping to ensure that AI tools are used responsibly and transparently. This technology supports the enforcement of policies that require authors to disclose the use of AI tools, thereby maintaining the integrity of scholarly work. SAGE, for instance, uses AI detection software to monitor and address potential misuse of AI in published articles [records: Entities (447), Relationships (447)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Collaboration between publishers and editorial bodies\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Publishers like SAGE and Springer Nature collaborate with editorial bodies such as COPE to develop and implement AI policies. These collaborations help ensure that AI tools are used in ways that align with ethical and scholarly standards. For example, COPE provides guidance that informs Springer Nature's AI policies, demonstrating the importance of structured oversight in AI governance [records: Entities (378, 449), Relationships (378, 449)].\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an expert in academic publishing and AI policy analysis. You are skilled at interpreting complex regulatory frameworks and identifying key stakeholders and their interactions. You are adept at helping people map out the relationships and structural dynamics within academic publishing ecosystems and AI governance policies.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive assessment report of a community taking on the role of a Role: A policy analyst that is examining the intersection of AI tools and academic publishing practices, given a text that outlines specific guidelines, responsibilities, and ethical considerations for authors, editors, and peer reviewers. The report will be used to inform stakeholders about the evolving landscape of AI in scholarly communication and to support the development of more inclusive and transparent policies.. The content of this report includes an overview of the community's key entities and relationships.\n\n# Report Structure\nThe report should include the following sections:\n- TITLE: community's name that represents its key entities - title should be short but specific. When possible, include representative named entities in the title.\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary of the community's overall structure, how its entities are related to each other, and significant points associated with its entities.\n- REPORT RATING: A float score between 0-10 that represents the relevance of the text to academic publishing rules, AI policy compliance, ethical guidelines, and institutional accountability, with 1 being trivial or irrelevant and 10 being highly significant, impactful, and essential for understanding and adhering to academic and AI governance standards.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the community. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format. Don't use any unnecessary escape sequences. The output should be a single JSON object that can be parsed by json.loads.\n    {\n        \"title\": \"<report_title>\",\n        \"summary\": \"<executive_summary>\",\n        \"rating\": <threat_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": \"<rating_explanation>\"\n        \"findings\": \"[{\"summary\":\"<insight_1_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_1_explanation\"}, {\"summary\":\"<insight_2_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_2_explanation\"}]\"\n    }\n\n# Grounding Rules\nAfter each paragraph, add data record reference if the content of the paragraph was derived from one or more data records. Reference is in the format of [records: <record_source> (<record_id_list>, ...<record_source> (<record_id_list>)]. If there are more than 10 data records, show the top 10 most relevant records.\nEach paragraph should contain multiple sentences of explanation and concrete examples with specific named entities. All paragraphs must have these references at the start and end. Use \"NONE\" if there are no related roles or records. Everything should be in English.\n\nExample paragraph with references added:\nThis is a paragraph of the output text [records: Entities (1, 2, 3), Claims (2, 5), Relationships (10, 12)]\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n5,ABILA CITY PARK,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n37,ABILA CITY PARK,POK RALLY,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n38,ABILA CITY PARK,POK,POK is holding a rally in Abila City Park\n39,ABILA CITY PARK,POKRALLY,The POKRally is taking place at Abila City Park\n40,ABILA CITY PARK,CENTRAL BULLETIN,Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park\n\nOutput:\n{\n    \"title\": \"Abila City Park and POK Rally\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community revolves around the Abila City Park, which is the location of the POK rally. The park has relationships with POK, POKRALLY, and Central Bulletin, all\nof which are associated with the rally event.\",\n    \"rating\": 5.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact rating is moderate due to the potential for unrest or conflict during the POK rally.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Abila City Park as the central location\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Abila City Park is the central entity in this community, serving as the location for the POK rally. This park is the common link between all other\nentities, suggesting its significance