chnology. It has established specific policies regarding the application of AI in the peer review and publication process, as well as in the preparation and review of submissions. These policies aim to ensure that AI supports editorial and publishing workflows without compromising research integrity. Additionally, EMERALD emphasizes ethical standards in research and publishing, integrating AI tools in a manner that upholds the quality and credibility of scholarly output.\",14\r\n27,ACCOUNTABILITY,\"The concept of **ACCOUNTABILITY** in academic publishing and AI governance refers to the shared responsibility of key stakeholders—including **authors, publishers, editors, and peer reviewers**—to uphold the ethical and intellectual standards of scholarly work. This includes ensuring that AI tools are used responsibly, that AI-generated content is accurate, original, and free from plagiarism, and that the final published work does not mislead readers. Additionally, these stakeholders are tasked with maintaining the accuracy, validity, and integrity of research throughout the publication process, from creation to evaluation. Accountability in this context emphasizes the collective duty to preserve trust in academic discourse, particularly as the integration of AI into research and publishing practices continues to evolve.\",9\r\n61,POLICY,\"The POLICY framework encompasses a range of guidelines and regulations established by various key stakeholders in academic publishing, including major publishers such as BMJ, Elsevier, Wiley, Emerald, Springer Nature, and Johns Hopkins University Press, as well as organizations like ISPOR, MIT Press, IEEE, and others. These policies address the ethical use of artificial intelligence (AI) and generative AI technologies, including large language models (LLMs), in the context of content submission, publication, and academic integrity. The guidelines cover critical areas such as transparency in AI usage, authorship responsibilities, disclosure requirements, copyright considerations, and restrictions on content creation. They aim to ensure accountability, maintain scholarly standards, and promote responsible integration of AI within academic publishing practices. The policies reflect a growing consensus among publishers and academic institutions to establish clear boundaries and ethical frameworks for the application of AI in research communication.\",33\r\n104,HUMAN OVERSIGHT,\"The practice of maintaining human control over AI-generated outcomes to prevent bias and ensure quality in academic publishing\"\"\",4\r\n106,ICMJE,\"An organization that sets guidelines for authors regarding the use of AI-assisted technologies in academic publishing\"\"\",4\r\n115,SAGE,\"SAGE is a publisher that collaborates with journal editors to investigate concerns regarding the misuse of AI in published articles. It recognizes the value of AI in research and writing but emphasizes the importance of ethical use and transparency, reflecting its commitment to responsible AI integration within academic publishing.\",2\r\n95,GENERIC AI POLICY,\"A general policy framework that outlines the ethical and transparent use of AI tools in academic publishing, including requirements for disclosure and accountability\"\"\",1\r\n108,IEEE,\"An organization that formulates and enforces guidelines for the use of AI-generated content in academic publications\"\"\",1\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n126,AUTHOR,EMERALD,Emerald requires authors to follow its policies on AI use during the submission and peer review process,73\r\n129,AUTHOR,ACCOUNTABILITY,\"Authors are accountable for the content of their manuscripts, including the use of AI tools, and are fully responsible for the originality, accuracy, and integrity of their work, including AI-generated content. This dual responsibility underscores the expectation that authors maintain ethical standards in research and publication, ensuring tha